TY  - JOUR
AU  - Hotchkiss, Edith S
AU  - Smith, David C
AU  - Strömberg, Per
T1  - Private Equity and the Resolution of Financial Distress
PY  - 2021
Y1  - 2021/12/01
DO  - 10.1093/rcfs/cfab015
JO  - The Review of Corporate Finance Studies
JA  - Review of Corporate Finance Studies
VL  - 10
IS  - 4
SP  - 694
EP  - 747
SN  - 2046-9128
AB  - We examine the role private equity (PE) sponsors play in the resolution of financial distress of portfolio companies. PE-backed firms have higher leverage and default at higher rates than other companies borrowing in leveraged loan markets. But, PE-backed firms restructure more quickly, avoid bankruptcy court more often, and liquidate less often compared to other highly leveraged firms experiencing financial distress. PE owners are also more likely to retain control post-restructuring, often by infusing capital as firms approach distress. While default frequencies are higher among PE-backed firms, PE investors appear to manage financial distress at lower cost compared to other owners. (JEL G23, G32, G33)
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rcfs/cfab015
ER  - 



